Document: GLTFLight
Path: godot/classes/class_gltflight.rst
Summary: Describes the properties of a GLTFLight, including its color, cone angles for spotlights, intensity, type, and range.

Property Descriptions
Method: set_color(value: Color)
Method: get_color() → Color
The color of the light in linear space. Defaults to white. A black color causes the light to have no effect. This value is linear to match glTF, but will be converted to nonlinear sRGB when creating a Godot Light3D node upon import, or converted to linear when exporting a Godot Light3D to glTF.

Method: set_inner_cone_angle(value: float)
Method: get_inner_cone_angle() → float
The inner angle of the cone in a spotlight. Must be less than or equal to the outer cone angle. Within this angle, the light is at full brightness. Between the inner and outer cone angles, there is a transition from full brightness to zero brightness. When creating a Godot SpotLight3D, the ratio between the inner and outer cone angles is used to calculate the attenuation of the light.

Method: set_intensity(value: float)
Method: get_intensity() → float
The intensity of the light. This is expressed in candelas (lumens per steradian) for point and spot lights, and lux (lumens per m²) for directional lights. When creating a Godot light, this value is converted to a unitless multiplier.

Method: set_light_type(value: String)
Method: get_light_type() → String
The type of the light. The values accepted by Godot are "point", "spot", and "directional", which correspond to Godot's OmniLight3D, SpotLight3D, and DirectionalLight3D respectively.

Method: set_outer_cone_angle(value: float)
Method: get_outer_cone_angle() → float
The outer angle of the cone in a spotlight. Must be greater than or equal to the inner angle. At this angle, the light drops off to zero brightness. Between the inner and outer cone angles, there is a transition from full brightness to zero brightness. If this angle is a half turn, then the spotlight emits in all directions. When creating a Godot SpotLight3D, the outer cone angle is used as the angle of the spotlight.

Method: set_range(value: float)
Method: get_range() → float
The range of the light, beyond which the light has no effect. glTF lights with no range defined behave like physical lights (which have infinite range). When creating a Godot light, the range is clamped to 4096.0.
